# WordPress WPBakery Redesign Project Rules
# =============================================

## Project Overview
- This is a WPBakery WordPress website redesign project
- Frontend design and UI components are the primary focus
- Backend functionality will be implemented by another developer later
- Use placeholder/replacement data until backend is ready

## Code Structure & Organization
- Follow the exact same pattern as existing WPBakery components in this project
- Place all shortcode files in `inc/wpbakery/shortcodes/` directory
- Use descriptive filenames ending with `_view.php` for shortcode views
- Include proper `require_once` statements in `inc/wpbakery/shortcodes.php`
- Maintain consistent file organization and naming conventions

## Frontend Design Focus
- Prioritize visual design, layout, and user experience
- Create responsive, in similar pattern like previous components
- Ensure accessibility standards (WCAG compliance)

## Placeholder Data Strategy
- Use online URLs for images if they dont exist in the assets folder, if i give you the image names then consider it, if not use online url (e.g., placeholder.com, unsplash.com)
- Create realistic sample content that represents final functionality
- Use descriptive placeholder text that shows content structure
- Include sample data arrays that backend developer can easily replace
- Add clear comments indicating where backend integration will happen

## WPBakery Integration
- Follow existing shortcode patterns in the project
- Use WordPress hooks and filters appropriately
- Implement proper shortcode registration and attributes
- Ensure compatibility with WPBakery page builder
- Follow WordPress coding standards and best practices

## CSS & Styling Guidelines
- Use BEM methodology for CSS class naming
- Implement CSS custom properties for consistent theming
- Create reusable component styles
- Ensure cross-browser compatibility
- Use semantic HTML structure

## CSS Variables & Figma Integration
- When implementing Figma designs, FIRST check if values already exist in variables.scss
- If the value exists in variables.scss, use the existing variable name
- If the value doesn't exist and it's a COLOR, create a new variable in variables.scss and use it
- when yyou check if it exist in the varialbes file, dont check the name, check the value, for example chceck if #fff exist then use the name it holds in the varialbles file
- If the value doesn't exist and it's NOT a color (spacing, typography, etc.), use the direct value from Figma
- Always prioritize using existing variables to maintain consistency across the project
- 

## JavaScript Guidelines
- Write clean, modular JavaScript code
- Use vanilla JavaScript or jQuery (as per project requirements)
- Implement proper event handling and DOM manipulation
- Add clear comments for backend integration points
- Ensure no conflicts with WordPress or WPBakery scripts

## File Naming Convention
- Shortcode files: `component_name_view.php`
- CSS files: `component-name.css`
- JavaScript files: `component-name.js`
- Follow existing naming patterns in the project


## Responsive Design
- Test on multiple screen sizes
- Use CSS media queries effectively
- Ensure touch-friendly interactions on mobile

## Accessibility
- Proper semantic HTML structure
- ARIA labels where appropriate
- Keyboard navigation support
- Color contrast compliance
- Screen reader friendly

## Browser Support
- Modern browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge)
- IE11+ if required by project specifications
- Graceful degradation for older browsers

## WordPress Integration
- Follow WordPress coding standards
- Use WordPress functions and hooks appropriately
- Ensure proper sanitization and validation
- Follow WordPress security best practices

## WPBakery Specific
- Test shortcodes in WPBakery page builder
- Ensure proper shortcode attribute handling
- Implement responsive breakpoints correctly
- Follow WPBakery design patterns and conventions

## Development Workflow
- Create frontend components first
- Add placeholder data and functionality
- Document integration points clearly
- Prepare for seamless backend handoff
- Maintain clean, readable code structure 